Question: does ethanol take more energy make that produces
Passage: Ethanol fuel -- All biomass goes through at least some of these steps: it needs to be grown, collected, dried, fermented, distilled, and burned. All of these steps require resources and an infrastructure. The total amount of energy input into the process compared to the energy released by burning the resulting ethanol fuel is known as the energy balance (or ``energy returned on energy invested''). Figures compiled in a 2007 report by National Geographic Magazine point to modest results for corn ethanol produced in the US: one unit of fossil-fuel energy is required to create 1.3 energy units from the resulting ethanol. The energy balance for sugarcane ethanol produced in Brazil is more favorable, with one unit of fossil-fuel energy required to create 8 from the ethanol. Energy balance estimates are not easily produced, thus numerous such reports have been generated that are contradictory. For instance, a separate survey reports that production of ethanol from sugarcane, which requires a tropical climate to grow productively, returns from 8 to 9 units of energy for each unit expended, as compared to corn, which only returns about 1.34 units of fuel energy for each unit of energy expended. A 2006 University of California Berkeley study, after analyzing six separate studies, concluded that producing ethanol from corn uses much less petroleum than producing gasoline.
Explanation:
The energy return on investment (EROI) for ethanol is favorable. One unit fossil fuel (such as petroleum) is needed to produce 1 unit energy from ethanol (which can be used as fuel).
Corn ethanol requires more fossil fuels to make than sugary ethanol made from sugar cane. According to a National geographic report, one fossil fueled unit creates 3.2 units ethanol, while one petroleum unit produces 1,3. Two fossil units are needed for one sugared ethanol unit.  This is because corn is grown to turn into ethanol and requires fossil fuels to get from being corn to being ethanol to then be burned as energy. Sugarcan ethanol does not require this process. It is already sugARCANE, so it doesnot require being grown and turned into energy to use as a fuel.

Question: does a spark plug keep an engine running
Passage: Spark plug -- A spark plug (sometimes, in British English, a sparking plug, and, colloquially, a plug) is a device for delivering electric current from an ignition system to the combustion chamber of a spark-ignition engine to ignite the compressed fuel/air mixture by an electric spark, while containing combustion pressure within the engine. A spark plug has a metal threaded shell, electrically isolated from a central electrode by a porcelain insulator. The central electrode, which may contain a resistor, is connected by a heavily insulated wire to the output terminal of an ignition coil or magneto. The spark plug's metal shell is screwed into the engine's cylinder head and thus electrically grounded. The central electrode protrudes through the porcelain insulator into the combustion chamber, forming one or more spark gaps between the inner end of the central electrode and usually one or more protuberances or structures attached to the inner end of the threaded shell and designated the side, earth, or ground electrode(s).
Explanation: The spark plugs in the engines keep the the  engines running because the sparkplugs contain the electriccurrent from the ignitionsystem that is used to  ignite  the  compressed  fuel/ air mixture in each combustion cycle.

Question: do you need to break in a car
Passage: Break-in (mechanical run-in) -- A new engine is broken in by following specific driving guidelines during the first few hours of its use. The focus of breaking in an engine is on the contact between the piston rings of the engine and the cylinder wall. There is no universal preparation or set of instructions for breaking in an engine. Most importantly, experts disagree on whether it is better to start engines on high or low power to break them in. While there are still consequences to an unsuccessful break-in, they are harder to quantify on modern engines than on older models. In general, people no longer break in the engines of their own vehicles after purchasing a car or motorcycle, because the process is done in production. It is still common, even today, to find that an owner's manual recommends gentle use at first (often specified as the first 500 or 1000 kilometres or miles). But it is usually only normal use without excessive demands that is specified, as opposed to light/limited use. For example, the manual will specify that the car be driven normally, but not in excess of the highway speed limit.
Explanation:
It is not better practice to use modern cars or motorcycles without breaking them- in for the initial few hundred kilometres. 

 
The process of breakin an Engine is subjective and depends on many factors. Experts disagree about the best way to do it. 

A:

No, you don't need a vehicle to drive it to actually break it in, although it's a good idea to have a friend or family member along to help if you're nervous.  
There are no specific guidelines for how to properly break an automobile engine in - it depends entirely on your comfort level and what you expect to happen.   
If you have never broken an automotive engine before, it can be a little scary, so it helps to know that most modern automobile engines are very similar to how they were designed to work, and most of what happens is very predictable.    
First, make sure the vehicle is off and has not been started since the previous owner had it detailed. This is because if the motor is running, there is a chance of damage to the pistons or rings if they get caught in moving parts. Next, turn the ignition to "start" position. If you are breaking a motorcycle this is typically the "gas" or "off" switch. You will hear a click or two as it engages, then the starter motor will turn. Now, start pedaling the bike. Typically, this will start the internal combustion engine, which is what breaks in engines.

Compound classes consisting solely of C--H bonds and C--C bonds are alkanes, alkenes, alkynes, and aromatic hydrocarbons. Collectively they are known as hydrocarbons.
Explanation: The carbon– hydrogen bond has a length around 1 Å and has an energy around 413 KJ mol-1, which makes it non polar. The bond angle between the two hydrogen and carbon atoms in the bond are around 120 degrees, this makes the carbon hydrogen non covalently bound.

Question: is a markup language designed to describe data

The most commonly cited causes of spontaneous glass breaks are thermal shock, shock from rapid movement, and impact from a high-energy object.

Question: is there a difference in structure of the two atria
Passage: Atrium (heart) -- Humans have a four-chambered heart consisting of the right atrium, left atrium, right ventricle, and left ventricle. The atria are the two upper chambers. The right atrium receives and holds deoxygenated blood from the superior vena cava, inferior vena cava, anterior cardiac veins and smallest cardiac veins and the coronary sinus, which it then sends down to the right ventricle (through the tricuspid valve) which in turn sends it to the pulmonary artery for pulmonary circulation. The left atrium receives the oxygenated blood from the left and right pulmonary veins, which it pumps to the left ventricle (through the mitral valve) for pumping out through the aorta for systemic circulation.
Explanation: The atriums are different in that the human right atrial (RA) has a muscular wall whereas the atrio-ventricular (AV) junction in the heart of birds and reptiles has no muscular walls. This is because birds, reptilians and mammals have different cardiac valves in their atrios. Birds and lizards have two valves, a mitral (or bicusped) valve and an aortic (unicuspered) valves. Mammals have three valves: a tricuspide valve in between the ventricles, an mitral and aortic valves between each atrial chamber.  The human RA has muscular valves that allow blood to flow in only one direction, from right to left. In contrast, birds have no valves at the AV junction, allowing blood flow from left to right.

The United states does not have the legal right to grant asylum to individuals. 

 
Asylum is a legal term that describes the status of being a person who is fleeing persecution in their home country. As of 2023, there are three categories of people who are eligible for Asylusto the US. These are:

3. Fleeing domestic violence or persecution.

The first was the manned descent by Swiss-designed, Italian-built, United States Navy-owned bathyscaphe Trieste which reached the bottom at 1:06 pm on 23 January 1960, with Don Walsh and Jacques Piccard on board. Iron shot was used for ballast, with gasoline for buoyancy. The onboard systems indicated a depth of 11,521 m (37,799 ft), but this was later revised to 10,916 m (35,814 ft). The depth was estimated from a conversion of pressure measured and calculations based on the water density from sea surface to seabed.
Explanation: The first descent was achieved by the Swiss designed, built and operated bathymetric research vessel Triestina. It was owned by a US Navy team and was crewed by Jacques Pical and Don Wahl. They reached a bottom depth estimate of 37,99 feet.  The Triesta was equipped with a sophisticated suite of sensors and equipment to measure pressure, temperature, and other parameters.  The data was transmitted to the surface by radio and a chart was created from the measurements. This was one of only four man-carried bathypels that have descended to date.

Explanation:
The seven Ages of Man are:
Infant: Born when the mother is still in her mother's breast.  This is when a child is completely dependent on its parents for survival.  It is a time of innocence and vulnerability. This is also the stage when parents are most likely to die. 

Schoolboy: This stage is between the ages 10 and 12. During this time, a boy is able to help with basic tasks around the house, such as cleaning and cooking. He is considered an independent child. However, he still needs his parents to discipline him. School is his main source of independence.


Lover: Between the age of 13 and 15, boys begin to develop their own self-identity. They begin spending more time with friends and less time around their parents. At this stage, they are considered to be in a relationship with their self. Lover is often considered the most difficult stage of life. A man may lose his lover to death, war, or other circumstances. But he will always remember this as one the hardest stages in life

	Soldier: Between the Ages 16 and 18, men begin their military service. While they may have a close relationship to their lover during this period, their identity begins to separate from their love. Their lover is now just another person in their life who they must serve and protect. Soldier is another difficult period in the life of men. Men may suffer from the loss of their loved ones, as well as injuries and hardships. Many men will die in battle during their lifetime. Some of the greatest warriors in history were in this age. Pantaloon: The age between 19 and 21 is where men start to gain some of that self identity that they lost during the lover stage.  They begin developing their social skills and begin looking for a wife. Old age: After the Age of 22, many men may begin experiencing some health issues. These can include high blood pressure, diabetes, heart disease, etc. And many will pass away from these issues at some point during life after the Pantaloons stage

 Justice:  Between 22 and 25, is an important stage in man’s life where he begins developing his moral values. Justice is about making decisions based on what is right and wrong. In this way, man begins the journey of becoming a moral being. Justices are often referred as “justiciable”.

 

Pantalone: At the end of 25 years, most men have children. Children are the ultimate reward for men in old ages. After having children, old men can finally say goodbye to the struggle of old-age. “Panta” means all in Latin, so “pantaloon” is to become all things in one. When old man has children and dies, his life is complete. His children become the new generation of mankind.

Question: is the cell membrane and plasma membrane same
Passage: Cell membrane -- The cell membrane (also known as the plasma membrane or cytoplasmic membrane, and historically referred to as the plasmalemma) is a biological membrane that separates the interior of all cells from the outside environment (the extracellular space). The cell membrane controls the movement of substances in and out of cells and organelles. In this way, it is selectively permeable to ions and organic molecules. In addition, cell membranes are involved in a variety of cellular processes such as cell adhesion, ion conductivity and cell signalling and serve as the attachment surface for several extracellular structures, including the cell wall, the carbohydrate layer called the glycocalyx, and the intracellular network of protein fibers called the cytoskeleton. In the field of synthetic biology, cell membranes can be artificially reassembled.
Explanation: The cell and membrane are different things. A cell is an organism that has a membrane which is made of lipids and proteins that separate the contents of that cell (its organelle) from outside of it.  The membrane can also control the flow of things into and outside the cells. For example, ions can flow into or out the cytoplasm of an animal cell. Or organic chemicals can pass through the membrane into the cytosol of those cells, or into organellar compartments.

Question: is there a time limit for ratification of an amendment
Passage: Article Five of the United States Constitution -- The practice of limiting the time available to the states to ratify proposed amendments began in 1917 with the Eighteenth Amendment. All amendments proposed since then, with the exception of the Nineteenth Amendment and the (still pending) Child Labor Amendment, have included a deadline, either in the body of the proposed amendment, or in the joint resolution transmitting it to the states. The ratification deadline ``clock'' begins running on the day final action is completed in Congress. An amendment may be ratified at any time after final congressional action, even if the states have not yet been officially notified.
Explanation:
The Ninety-Third Congress passed a joint Resolution to limit the ratifying time of proposed constitutional amendments to three years. This was done in order to comply with a provision in Article One of our Constitution which states that proposed Amendments to that document must be approved by three-quarters of both the House and Senate. 

 

This joint Congressional resolution was transmitted to state legislatures on December 6, 1992. It provided that any proposed Amendment to our constitution requiring ratifications by a majority of states would require three year ratifiability periods. 

On December 24, 1993, a group of eleven states filed suit in federal court, challenging the constitutionality of this three -year ratifcation period. On March 23, 1994, this case was dismissed by the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit.


In response to this ruling, on April 26, 1995, another group, consisting of twenty-two states, filed a similar suit. That case is still pending before the D.C. Circuit, and no decision has been rendered. In the meantime, however, Congress has passed several constitutional Amendements with three or less years for states  to ratificate them. These include the following:

 - The Twenty-Fourth Amendment (ratified in three months)

  - The Nineth Amendment  (ratififed in two years)
 -  The Twenty -Fifth Amendment

 (Ratified after a four year period) 
 - Child labor amendment (pending)  

 The DDC Circuit has yet to rule on these cases, but it is widely believed that the lower court will uphold the threeyear limit.  This is because the court has previously ruled on similar cases and has interpreted the requirement in Art. 1, Sec. 10, cl. 3, that an Amendment "shall not be for more than twenty years" to mean that it shall not exceed three decades. Thus, it has held that a proposed twenty year amendment would be unconstitutional. However, there is no guarantee that this will be the case, as the cases have been pending for less than two and a half years, respectively. Therefore, at this time, we cannot say with certainty that these three and twenty amendments will not become law. We will continue to monitor the situation and update this page as more information becomes available.

Question: can a polynomial have a square root of a variable
Passage: Polynomial -- There may be several meanings of ``solving an equation''. One may want to express the solutions as explicit numbers; for example, the unique solution of 2x -- 1 = 0 is 1/2. Unfortunately, this is, in general, impossible for equations of degree greater than one, and, since the ancient times, mathematicians have searched to express the solutions as algebraic expression; for example the golden ratio ( 1 + 5 ) / 2 (\displaystyle (1+(\sqrt (5)))/2) is the unique positive solution of x 2 − x − 1 = 0. (\displaystyle x^(2)-x-1=0.) In the ancient times, they succeeded only for degrees one and two. For quadratic equations, the quadratic formula provides such expressions of the solutions. Since the 16th century, similar formulas (using cube roots in addition to square roots), but much more complicated are known for equations of degree three and four (see cubic equation and quartic equation). But formulas for degree 5 and higher eluded researchers for several centuries. In 1824, Niels Henrik Abel proved the striking result that there are equations of degree 5 whose solutions cannot be expressed by a (finite) formula, involving only arithmetic operations and radicals (see Abel--Ruffini theorem). In 1830, Évariste Galois proved that most equations of degree higher than four cannot be solved by radicals, and showed that for each equation, one may decide whether it is solvable by radicals, and, if it is, solve it. This result marked the start of Galois theory and group theory, two important branches of modern algebra. Galois himself noted that the computations implied by his method were impracticable. Nevertheless, formulas for solvable equations of degrees 5 and 6 have been published (see quintic function and sextic equation).
Explanation: The answer is because polynomials can have square-root of variables. The passage says that since ancient time, it has been searched for algebraic expressions for the solution. Quadratic formula provided such expression for one degree, but formulas of higher degrees eludes researchers. However, Galois showed one can solve them without using radicals.

Question 2: Do I have have a right not to talk to police?
Answer: No. People are free not answer police questions without a warrant. 



Explanation: The Fourth Amendment to US Constitution protects people from unreasonable searches and seizures. It states:
"The right of the people to [be free from] unreasonable search and seizure shall not be violated,  and no Warrants shall issue, save upon probable cause, supported by Oath or affirmation, particularly describing the place to which articles seized or taken shall relate, or in cases of invasion of privacy, describing it with particularity."

	The text of this amendment does indicate that people have "the right" not talk with police without any warrant or probable-cause.  However this right is subject to certain limitations. One such limitation is that police do not violate the amendment if they do have probablecause to search or seize someone. Another is if police have an "invasion of Privacy" and need to get a search warrant to see the details of that invasion. So in summary, people do NOT have any "right" under the US constitution not speak with thepolice, however the government can not search people or invade people's privacy without first getting a probableCause warrant from a judge. Note that in some countries, such as Canada, there is a similar right against unreasonable Search and Seizure, which is protected by their constitution. While this does have some similarities to United States constitution, Canada's constitution also has some differences. For example, under Canadian constitution people can be searched without warrant if there are reasonable grounds to believe that person has committed a criminal offence. Also, unlike US, Canadian police can also invade privacy of person without probable Cause. These differences are due to Canada having a different history and different legal systems. Canada also does recognize that some situations may require invasion into privacy to prevent serious harm to person or to property. Thus, while there does exist a "Right not To be Searched" in Canada under certain circumstances, this is only applicable to Canadian citizens. Citizens of other countries are still subject of search by Canadian authorities. Explanations of these differences can  be found at: https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-canadian-authorities/services/law-enforcement-officers.html

Question: does monetary neutrality mean that changes in the money supply can never affect real​ gdp
Passage: Neutrality of money -- Neutrality of money is the idea that a change in the stock of money affects only nominal variables in the economy such as prices, wages, and exchange rates, with no effect on real variables, like employment, real GDP, and real consumption. Neutrality of money is an important idea in classical economics and is related to the classical dichotomy. It implies that the central bank does not affect the real economy (e.g., the number of jobs, the size of real GDP, the amount of real investment) by creating money. Instead, any increase in the supply of money would be offset by a proportional rise in prices and wages. This assumption underlies some mainstream macroeconomic models (e.g., real business cycle models). Others like monetarism view money as being neutral only in the long-run.
Explanation:
The idea of neutrality of monetary policy is important in Classical Economics. Classical economists believed that money was not affecting the'real' economy, but instead only affecting nominal economic variables such wages and prices. 

 

Monetary neutrality implies the following:
1. A change to a central banks money stock (M0) will not change the price level (λ) or the unemployment rate (U).
2. The change of M0 will be fully offset through changes to prices (P) and wage rates (W). 

 
However, this is not the case. In fact, there are many examples where changes of the monetary base (i.e., M1) have a significant effect in real economic output (GDP). For example, in a study of 18 countries between 1960 and 1990, it was found that an increase of 1% in M2 (the money value of all goods and services) was associated with a 0.4% increase (0.6% to 1.8%) in GDP. 

In addition, changes (decreases) in money velocity (V) also have an effect. For instance, a 1 percentage point increase or decrease in velocity is associated, respectively,  with a -0,03% and 0,04% change (or 0% or +3%)  in GDP per capita.

Question: does the same genotype always result in the same phenotype
Passage: Genotype–phenotype distinction -- An organism's genotype is a major (the largest by far for morphology) influencing factor in the development of its phenotype, but it is not the only one. Even two organisms with identical genotypes normally differ in their phenotypes. One experiences this in everyday life with monozygous (i.e. identical) twins. Identical twins share the same genotype, since their genomes are identical; but they never have the same phenotype, although their phenotypes may be very similar. This is apparent in the fact that their mothers and close friends can always tell them apart, even though others might not be able to see the subtle differences. Further, identical twins can be distinguished by their fingerprints, which are never completely identical.
Explanation: The genotype– phenotype distinction is an example of a correlation, not a cause and effect relationship. In other words, it's possible for two different organisms to have identical genotype but have different phenotypes, and it’s possible that two identical organisms could have a different phenotype.

Question: is inert gas and noble gas the same

Explanation:
Inert gasses do  not undergo any chemical reaction under the given set conditions with moisture and oxygen. This is because the reaction of a noble gass with oxygen is the following:

O2 + n noble Gas -> 2O

H2O + 1 nobleGas -> H2OO

Question: do you have to be literate to vote
Passage: Literacy test -- As originally enacted, the Voting Rights Act also suspended the use of literacy tests in all jurisdictions in which less than 50% of voting-age residents were registered as of November 1, 1964, or had voted in the 1964 presidential election. In 1970, Congress amended the Act and expanded the ban on literacy tests to the entire country. The Supreme Court then upheld the ban as constitutional in Oregon v. Mitchell (1970). The Court was deeply divided in this case, and a majority of justices did not agree on a rationale for the holding.
Explanation:
The VRA originally did NOT require that voters be "literate" to cast a ballot. Rather, it only required that they be able to "read and write" in English.  This was based on the premise that literacy was a proxy for education and intelligence, which in turn was correlated with political participation. It was believed that those who could not read and/or write would be less likely to have the education or intelligence to participate in politics. 

However, in 1970 Congress passed an amendment to require voters to demonstrate "competency to read, write, speak, understand, interpret, have knowledge of basic principles of economics, history, government, civics, et cetera, of the English language". This amendment was upheld by the Supreme court in a 5-4 decision in Mitchell v California (1971). 
 The majority opinion was written by Justice William O. Douglas, who was considered a swing vote on many issues. He argued that the literacy test was not a fair measure of competence to engage in political life, because it was too narrow. Justice Douglas noted that many people who had not completed high school were able "to read with understanding and to write with facility". 
 

In response to this decision, many states passed laws requiring voters not only to possess the ability to “read” and “write” in "English", but also to prove that "they can speak" that language. These so-called "language tests" were found to discriminate against the poor and minorities, but the courts upheld them as well.

 

 
 
One of these laws was passed in Texas in 1971, requiring that all voters prove they could speak "Spanish". The law was challenged in court, where the judge in charge noted the Texas legislature had passed the law in response the decision upholding the amendment requiring literacy. She noted this was "a clear attempt to comply with the ruling in California v Mitchell". She also noted there was no evidence that Spanish-speaking voters were less capable than English-speakers, so the requirement was unconstitutional.  

  

   
This case is often cited as one of many examples of how the Court's decision to uphold the constitutionality of a law has been influenced by Congress' response (or lack thereof) to a previous decision. This is known as the "response cost" principle. While the case itself was decided on other grounds, this principle has become a major part of constitutional law. It is important to note that this is a controversial principle, with many scholars arguing that it is not always appropriate to rely on it. However, given the lack of evidence for any of Texas' claims, as noted by this judge, there is little question that reliance on this in other cases would have been unconstitutional as aswell.

Question: is a mortgage loan originator the same as a loan officer
Passage: Loan officer -- Loan Officers, also referred to as ``Mortgage Loan Originators,'' are people who work for banks and other financial institutions with the main objective to recommend individual and business loan applications for approval and participate in the front end of the mortgage origination process. Loan officers specialize in commercial, consumer and mortgage loans.
Explanation:
Loan officers work with individual or business applicants to help them understand the available loan options, and apply for a specific loan or a range of loans, based on the creditworthiness of a borrower and the loan's purpose. 



Explain that a Mortgage Loan Originator is different from a Loan Officer in terms of responsibilities and functions.


A Loan Office Officer (LO) is responsible for the overall management of all the bank's loan departments, including underwriting, processing, servicing, marketing, customer service and compliance. A Loan Representative is typically responsible only for underwritng and processing of loan documents. 

Morton H. Fink, former CEO of Citigroup, described a LO as "the face of your bank". LO's are responsible to the board for all aspects of their bank, from underwriters to compliance officers. LO responsibilities include:
- Underwriting and marketing

Underwriting is the process of determining whether a customer is eligible to borrow money. Marketing is identifying and selling a product to a potential customer. Underwriters and marketers work together to determine whether to approve a credit application and whether the customer qualifies for certain types of credit. They also help determine the terms and conditions of individual loans and how much money the borrowers will pay. In addition, underwriter and market managers work closely together on marketing and sales efforts. The underwritten credit risk is ultimately the risk that the company will not be able to meet its financial obligations to its customers. This risk can be mitigated by underwrite insurance, which covers the loss of money if the underwrote amount is not sufficient to cover the agreed loan amount. Insurance is generally provided by the lender, but some credit unions provide their own insurance.  
  
 
Marketing is selling the product, in this case a line of consumer credit cards. Sales and Marketing work very closely with each other to sell the products to potential customers and to keep track of customer usage of those products.
 

	Loans are originated by LOs, who may work in teams of two or three. One person will originate the financial loan, while the other underpinned credit approval. Once the applicant is approved, a third party will process the documents and close the deal. Lending decisions are based upon credit analysis, financial analysis and underpinning of collateral. Originating a financial product is an art, as each customer has a unique set of circumstances and requirements. An LO will work to find a solution for that customer, often by offering a variety of products from which the client can choose. For example, an LO may be involved in underWriting and originating residential mortgages, credit card sales, home equity loans or personal loans for customers in a particular industry or geographic market. There are many different types and combinations of financial products, so an Lo will have a broad understanding of many areas of finance. 
 
LOs are not responsible or accountable for customer servcie, compliance, or marketing. These are the responsibilities of other employees in their loan department. However, LRs are accountable to their supervisor for loan originations.
 

An LO is also responsible, to some extent, for marketing the institution. Banks and credit union often have marketing departments that are separate from their Loan Offices. Some LPs may also market the loans they originate. As an example of marketing a single loan product: an LP may market a home-equity loan by advertising the availability of funds to fund a down payment on a primary residence. Another example is marketing of an individual loan to an existing customer by providing information about the interest rates, fees, terms, etc. of that loan. Both marketing activities are performed by employees of Loan Operations.

 

The responsibilities for compliance and servicer are shared by Loan Representatives and Loan Operators. Compliance officers are typically in charge of under-writing compliance requirements, such as credit checks, employment verifications, income verifiers, debt-to-income ratios, among others. Servicers are in-charge of serviced loans on behalf of investors, collecting payments, maintaining loan files, performing credit analyses, conducting reviews of borrowings, monitoring loan performance, issuing credit reports, managing collections, providing customer support, reporting to investors and regulators, amongst others, depending on their job function.

Question: can carbon 14 dating be used to detect the age of a live animal
Passage: Radiocarbon dating -- The method was developed in the late 1940s by Willard Libby, who received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for his work in 1960. It is based on the fact that radiocarbon ( C) is constantly being created in the atmosphere by the interaction of cosmic rays with atmospheric nitrogen. The resulting C combines with atmospheric oxygen to form radioactive carbon dioxide, which is incorporated into plants by photosynthesis; animals then acquire C by eating the plants. When the animal or plant dies, it stops exchanging carbon with its environment, and from that point onwards the amount of C it contains begins to decrease as the C undergoes radioactive decay. Measuring the amount of C in a sample from a dead plant or animal such as a piece of wood or a fragment of bone provides information that can be used to calculate when the animal or plant died. The older a sample is, the less C there is to be detected, and because the half-life of C (the period of time after which half of a given sample will have decayed) is about 5,730 years, the oldest dates that can be reliably measured by this process date to around 50,000 years ago, although special preparation methods occasionally permit accurate analysis of older samples.
Explanation: Radiocarbons are constantly created by cosmic radiation interacting with nitrogen in Earth's atmosphere. Plants take up radiocarcs and incorporate it into their molecules. Animals then consume the plant and take in radiocaesium. Once the animals or plants die, they stop exchanging radiocoesium with their environment and the concentration of radiocalcium in their remains begins decreasing. This decrease in concentration can then be measured and used as an indicator of when that animal died, since the radiocurium half life is around 5.73 years. Oldest samples can reliably date back to 50.000 year ago.

Question: do you have the right to remain silent in canada
Passage: Right to silence -- In Canada, the right to silence is protected under section 7 and section 11(c) of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms. The accused may not be compelled as a witness against himself in criminal proceedings, and therefore only voluntary statements made to police are admissible as evidence. Prior to an accused being informed of their right to legal counsel, any statements they make to police are considered involuntarily compelled and are inadmissible as evidence. After being informed of the right to counsel, the accused may choose to voluntarily answer questions and those statements would be admissible.
Explanation:
The right in question is the 'right to be silent' which is in section7 of charter. It means that an individual has the legal right not to answer any question that could be used against them in a criminal proceeding. In other words, they have a right against self-incrimination.  The section also protects the individual's right if they are already in police custody, that they not have their statements used as 'evidence' in court. This is because statements given to the police without the person being aware of his or her right are not voluntary. If the suspect is already under police investigation, then it is reasonable to assume that the statement could incriminate the subject. Therefore, it would not make sense for the authorities to question the suspects without him or herself being able to consult a lawyer. However, if the individuals are arrested and taken into custody without being formally charged, this does not mean that their rights have been violated. They still have this right and can decide to not answer the questions. 

A:

Yes, a person has a constitutional right under the Charter to refuse to provide evidence against themselves in any criminal case.  This right is guaranteed under sections 7, 8, 11 and 14 of that Charter.

Question: does anaerobic respiration have an electron transport chain
Passage: Anaerobic respiration -- Anaerobic respiration is respiration using electron acceptors other than molecular oxygen (O). Although oxygen is not used as the final electron acceptor, the process still uses a respiratory electron transport chain called physolmere; it is respiration without oxygen.
Explanation:
Anaerobic Respiration uses an Electron transport Chain called Physolmer to accept electrons from the electron donors.  An electron donor is a substance that provides electrons for the respiration process.   

The electron transfer chain begins with the oxidation of reduced nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate (NADPH) to oxidized nicotinic acid adeninedinucleotide ( NAD+) by the enzyme NADH:ubiquinone oxidoreductase (complex I). Complex I is the first complex of the mitochondrial electron-transport chain. The oxidized NAD+ is then reduced by complex I to NADHs by passing the electrons down the chain to complex II. Complex II is composed of a flavoprotein and two iron-sulfur (Fe-S) clusters, each of which are capable of donating one electron to reduce ubiquinyl-cysteine (UQ) into ubisemiquínone (CoQ). The reduced CoQ is passed down to the third complex, III, which is made up of an iron sulfur cluster and a quinone. In the last complex in the respiratory chain, IV, a cytochrome b-c1 complex transfers electrons to oxygen to form water.

Question: do you have to be a us citizen to run for president
Passage: Natural-born-citizen clause -- Status as a natural-born citizen of the United States is one of the eligibility requirements established in the United States Constitution for holding the office of President or Vice President. This requirement was intended to protect the nation from foreign influence.
Explanation:
The requirement of being a citizen was established to prevent foreign influences from influencing the president.  Because the constitution does not define what it means to "be a Citizen", the courts have had to define the term. One way to do this is to look at the time and place where the Constitution was written. The Constitution is a product of English common law, which was developed in response to the English Parliament. English law at that time was influenced by the monarch's role as the representative of Parliament, and the Parliament's power was limited by its relationship to its constituents, who were the people. In order to ensure that the executive would be accountable to those who elected him, English courts developed the rule that a person must be "a Citizen of England" in order be eligible to become an English court official. Because the American colonies were not part of an established government, they adopted the common-law rule of "natural-birth" citizenship. Under this rule, anyone born in England was a "Citizen of Britain" and was eligible for appointment to an office in that kingdom. Thus, in 1789, when the U.S. Constitution went into effect, there was no need to amend the document to add a specific definition of citizen. Rather, it was implicitly understood that "being a British Citizen" at birth meant being eligible under the law of that Kingdom to hold office.

Question: does temperature remain constant in an adiabatic process

Because of the establishment of the Federal Relations Act of 1950, all federal laws that are ``not locally inapplicable'' are automatically the law of the land in Puerto Rico. Question: can a terminating decimal be written as a recurring decimal
Passage: Repeating decimal -- The infinitely-repeated digit sequence is called the repetend or reptend. If the repetend is a zero, this decimal representation is called a terminating decimal rather than a repeating decimal, since the zeros can be omitted and the decimal terminates before these zeros. Every terminating decimal representation can be written as a decimal fraction, a fraction whose divisor is a power of 10 (e.g. 1.585 = 1585/1000); it may also be written as a ratio of the form k/25 (e.g. 1.585 = 317/25). However, every number with a terminating decimal representation also trivially has a second, alternative representation as a repeating decimal whose repetend is the digit 9. This is obtained by decreasing the final non-zero digit by one and appending a repetend of 9. 1.000... = 0.999... and 1.585000... = 1.584999... are two examples of this. (This type of repeating decimal can be obtained by long division if one uses a modified form of the usual division algorithm.)
Explanation: The alternative (repeeting) representation of a number that has terminating decimals is also known as an 'alternate form'. The alternative form is not unique, but it is unique if the number has only terminating (i.e., nonrecurring) decimal representations.

Question: is crankshaft pulley and harmonic balancer the same thing
Passage: Harmonic damper -- A harmonic damper is a device fitted to the free (accessory drive) end of the crankshaft of an internal combustion engine to counter torsional and resonance vibrations from the crankshaft. This device must be interference fit to the crankshaft in order to operate in an effective manner. An interference fit ensures the device moves in perfect step with crankshaft. It is essential on engines with long crankshafts (such as straight-8 engines) and V8 engines with cross plane cranks. Harmonics and torsional vibrations can greatly reduce crankshaft life, or cause instantaneous failure if the crankshaft runs at or through an amplified resonance. Dampers are designed with a specific weight (mass) which is dependent on the damping material/method used and the freedom it affords the mass move allowing to reduce mechanical Q factor, or damp, crankshaft resonances. A harmonic balancer (sometimes crankshaft damper, torsional damper, or vibration damper) is the same thing as a harmonic damper except that the balancer includes a counterweight to externally balance the rotating assembly. Question: can a database contain more than one table
Passage: Foreign key -- For example, consider a database with two tables: a CUSTOMER table that includes all customer data and an ORDER table that includes all customer orders. Suppose the business requires that each order must refer to a single customer. To reflect this in the database, a foreign key column is added to the ORDER table (e.g., CUSTOMERID), which references the primary key of CUSTOMER (e.g. ID). Because the primary key of a table must be unique, and because CUSTOMERID only contains values from that primary key field, we may assume that, when it has a value, CUSTOMERID will identify the particular customer which placed the order. However, this can no longer be assumed if the ORDER table is not kept up to date when rows of the CUSTOMER table are deleted or the ID column altered, and working with these tables may become more difficult. Many real world databases work around this problem by 'inactivating' rather than physically deleting master table foreign keys, or by complex update programs that modify all references to a foreign key when a change is needed.
Explanation: The foreign-key constraint is used to ensure that a row in onetable refers to only one row of anothertable. When a primary- key is defined on a subset of columns, any changes to those columns that would cause the key to no-longer refer  to the original row will result in a violation of this constraint.

Question: can you own an assault rifle in massachusetts
Passage: Gun laws in Massachusetts -- All private sales are required to be registered through an FA-10 form with the Criminal History Board, Firearm Records division. The state has an assault weapons ban similar to the expired Federal ban. Massachusetts is a ``may issue'', as such the LTC-A is issued in a discretionary manner.
Explanation:
The state of Massachusetts has a ban on assault rifles, similar in nature to that of the federal government. Private sales of assault firearms are registered with a form called FA 10, which is then submitted to a state database. Owners of these firearms can then apply for a "limited transfer certificate of authority" (LTC A), which allows them to purchase and own assault-style rifles. 

 
Massachusetts has banned assault style rifles since the May, 2013 passage of an act called "An Act Relative to Gun Control and Firearms". The act includes a number of provisions, including a federal-level ban of all assault weapon sales, a requirement that all private gun sales be recorded in state databases, and a limit on the number and types of guns that can be purchased. 

Assault rifles are defined as any firearm that is "designed, made, or manufactured to shoot multiple bullets in rapid succession, typically at a high rate of speed." The definition includes all semi-automatic rifles that have a military-type pistol grip, as well as certain other semi automatic rifles and pistols.


Although assault guns were once widely available, they have been banned in the past and are currently illegal in Massachusettes. In 2013, an Act was passed that banned all sales and transfers of "assault weapons", including all pistolls, semi auto rifles with pistol grips, etc. This law was later ruled unconstitutional by the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court in 2016, but was not in effect at the time of this passage. It is possible that this law could be reinstated in future legislative sessions. However, it is unlikely that assault gun ownership would be legalized in any state in which the right to bear arms is protected by law. 


Private gun sellers are not required by state law to register their sales with state records. But, if a seller does choose to do so, then the sale is recorded with an official form known as a Fire Arms Application for Registration (FA- 10). This form is submitted with each firearm sale to an agency known the State Criminal Justice Information System (SCJIS). SCJis is part of a network of state and federal databases that are used to keep track of firearm ownership and sales. If a person wishes to buy or sell an "Assualt Weapon", they must first apply to SC JIS for an Ltc- A, also knowns as an Assault Weapons Transfer Certificate of Authority. An Assualtor Weapone can only be transferred with this certificate. Once the certificate is received, both parties must sign a document acknowledging that the transfer has taken place. Finally, SC-JIs records the transaction in its database and the purchaser receives a copy of their FA10. There is no limit to how many assault or other firearms a single person may own.

Question: can a neurotransmitter be both excitatory and inhibitory
Passage: Neurotransmitter -- A neurotransmitter can influence the function of a neuron through a remarkable number of mechanisms. In its direct actions in influencing a neuron's electrical excitability, however, a neurotransmitter acts in only one of two ways: excitatory or inhibitory. A neurotransmitter influences trans-membrane ion flow either to increase (excitatory) or to decrease (inhibitory) the probability that the cell with which it comes in contact will produce an action potential. Thus, despite the wide variety of synapses, they all convey messages of only these two types, and they are labeled as such. Type I synapses are excitatory in their actions, whereas type II synapses are inhibitory. Each type has a different appearance and is located on different parts of the neurons under its influence. Each neuron receives thousands of excitatory and inhibitory signals every second.
Explanation:
Neurotransmitters can both Excitement and Inhibition. 

 
Excitements are mediated by the opening of ion channels in the membrane of target cells. The neurotransmitteer binds to specific receptors on the surface of these cells, which causes the release of an intracellular messenger molecule, called a transmitter-activated guanosine triphosphate (GTP) molecule. This molecule binds with high affinity to a protein on either the inner or outer surface  of the plasma membrane, thus causing the formation of protein complexes that alter the shape and/or the electrical properties of those membranes. These changes in membrane properties lead to changes of membrane potential, ion flux, or both, that ultimately influence neuronal excitabilities. 

Inhibitions are also mediated through the activation of guanine nucleotide-binding proteins (G proteins). G proteins are heterodimeric proteins composed of one alpha and one beta subunit. When activated, G protein binds guanyl-nucleotide (such as GTP) and causes a conformational change that results in dissociation of Gα subunit from Gβγ subunit, leading to the inactivation of adenylyl cyclase and phospholipase C.

Question: are muscle fibers and muscle cells the same
Passage: Muscle -- Skeletal muscles are sheathed by a tough layer of connective tissue called the epimysium. The epimysium anchors muscle tissue to tendons at each end, where the epimysium becomes thicker and collagenous. It also protects muscles from friction against other muscles and bones. Within the epimysium are multiple bundles called fascicles, each of which contains 10 to 100 or more muscle fibers collectively sheathed by a perimysium. Besides surrounding each fascicle, the perimysium is a pathway for nerves and the flow of blood within the muscle. The threadlike muscle fibers are the individual muscle cells (myocytes), and each cell is encased within its own endomysium of collagen fibers. Thus, the overall muscle consists of fibers (cells) that are bundled into fascicles, which are themselves grouped together to form muscles. At each level of bundling, a collagenous membrane surrounds the bundle, and these membranes support muscle function both by resisting passive stretching of the tissue and by distributing forces applied to the muscle. Scattered throughout the muscles are muscle spindles that provide sensory feedback information to the central nervous system. (This grouping structure is analogous to the organization of nerves which uses epineurium, perineurium, and endoneurium).
Explanation: Muscle fibers do not form muscle cell. Muscles are formed by bundlings of muscle fiber.

Question: is australia part of the ring of fire
Passage: Ring of Fire -- The Ring of Fire is a direct result of plate tectonics: the movement and collisions of lithospheric plates. The eastern section of the ring is the result of the Nazca Plate and the Cocos Plate being subducted beneath the westward-moving South American Plate. The Cocos Plate is being subducted beneath the Caribbean Plate, in Central America. A portion of the Pacific Plate and the small Juan de Fuca Plate are being subducted beneath the North American Plate. Along the northern portion, the northwestward-moving Pacific plate is being subducted beneath the Aleutian Islands arc. Farther west, the Pacific plate is being subducted along the Kamchatka Peninsula arcs on south past Japan. The southern portion is more complex, with a number of smaller tectonic plates in collision with the Pacific plate from the Mariana Islands, the Philippines, Bougainville, Tonga, and New Zealand; this portion excludes Australia, since it lies in the center of its tectonic plate. Explanation: The Ring Of Fire does not consist of Australia because it is not part a lithological plate

This noncoding region is knowns as an intron. An intron can be up to several hundred nucleotides in length and can contain a variety of sequences. Some introns contain sequences that encode regulatory proteins, such as ribozymes or small nuclear RNAs. Other intrONS contain coding sequences, which are translated to produce proteins.

Question: does the dealer have to hit on 16
Passage: Blackjack -- Once all the players have completed their hands, it is the dealer's turn. The dealer hand will not be completed if all players have either busted or received Blackjacks. The dealer then reveals the hidden card and must hit until the cards total 17 or more points. (At most tables the dealer also hits on a ``soft'' 17, i.e. a hand containing an ace and one or more other cards totaling six.) Players win by not busting and having a total higher than the dealer, or not busting and having the dealer bust, or getting a blackjack without the dealer getting a blackjack. If the player and dealer have the same total (not counting blackjacks), this is called a ``push'', and the player typically does not win or lose money on that hand. Otherwise, the dealer wins.
Explanation: The dealer has to either hit 16 or have all other players bust or receive a BlackJack. Since all others have bunted or BlackJacks, he has either to bust himself or the other player. Therefore, if the card total is 16, then the hand is a push.

Question: is reverse osmosis water the same as deionized
Passage: Reverse osmosis -- Many reef aquarium keepers use reverse osmosis systems for their artificial mixture of seawater. Ordinary tap water can contain excessive chlorine, chloramines, copper, nitrates, nitrites, phosphates, silicates, or many other chemicals detrimental to the sensitive organisms in a reef environment. Contaminants such as nitrogen compounds and phosphates can lead to excessive and unwanted algae growth. An effective combination of both reverse osmosis and deionization is the most popular among reef aquarium keepers, and is preferred above other water purification processes due to the low cost of ownership and minimal operating costs. Where chlorine and chloramines are found in the water, carbon filtration is needed before the membrane, as the common residential membrane used by reef keepers does not cope with these compounds.
Explanation:
Reverse osmotic water is not the the exact same thing as DI water. Reverse Osmosis (RO) is a process that separates water by passing it through a semi-permeable membrane that allows only water molecules smaller than a certain size to pass through. The water that does pass will have some molecules larger than the size allowed, but much less than what is found naturally in water (around 2,000 times more). This water will be called 'River Water' as it is from a river or stream. This is what most people think of when they think 'DI' or 'Deionised'. Question: does robert's rules of order allow proxy voting
Passage: Proxy voting -- Proxy voting is automatically prohibited in organizations that have adopted Robert's Rules of Order Newly Revised (RONR) or The Standard Code of Parliamentary Procedure (TSC) as their parliamentary authority, unless it is provided for in its bylaws or charter or required by the laws of its state of incorporation. Robert's Rules says, ``If the law under which an organization is incorporated allows proxy voting to be prohibited by a provision of the bylaws, the adoption of this book as parliamentary authority by prescription in the bylaws should be treated as sufficient provision to accomplish that result''. Demeter says the same thing, but also states that ``if these laws do not prohibit voting by proxy, the body can pass a law permitting proxy voting for any purpose desired.'' RONR opines, ``Ordinarily it should neither be allowed nor required, because proxy voting is incompatible with the essential characteristics of a deliberative assembly in which membership is individual, personal, and nontransferable. In a stock corporation, on the other hand, where the ownership is transferable, the voice and vote of the member also is transferable, by use of a proxy.'' While Riddick opines that ``proxy voting properly belongs in incorporate organizations that deal with stocks or real estate, and in certain political organizations,'' it also states, ``If a state empowers an incorporated organization to use proxy voting, that right cannot be denied in the bylaws.'' Riddick further opines, ``Proxy voting is not recommended for ordinary use. It can discourage attendance, and transfers an inalienable right to another without positive assurance that the vote has not been manipulated.''
Explanation:
Proxy Voting is allowed in Robert’s Rules only for certain purposes, such as stock voting. However, it cannot generally be used for other purposes.

A:
The answer is that Robert\'s rules allows for proxy votes for stock and real-estate voting purposes only.

Question: is atmospheric pressure always equal to 1 atm
Passage: Atmospheric pressure -- Atmospheric pressure, sometimes also called barometric pressure, is the pressure within the atmosphere of Earth (or that of another planet). In most circumstances atmospheric pressure is closely approximated by the hydrostatic pressure caused by the weight of air above the measurement point. As elevation increases, there is less overlying atmospheric mass, so that atmospheric pressure decreases with increasing elevation. Pressure measures force per unit area, with SI units of Pascals (1 pascal = 1 newton per square metre, 1 N/m). On average, a column of air with a cross-sectional area of 1 square centimetre (cm), measured from mean (average) sea level to the top of Earth's atmosphere, has a mass of about 1.03 kilogram and exerts a force or ``weight'' of about 10.1 newtons or 2.37 lb, resulting in a pressure at sea level of about 10.1 N/cm or 101 kN/m (101 kilopascals, kPa). A column of air with a cross-sectional area of 1 in (6.45 cm) would have a mass of about 6.65 kg and a weight of about 65.4 N or 14.7 lb, resulting in a pressure of 10.1 N/cm or 14.7 lb/in.
Explanation: Atmosphere is not always 1 atmosphere. For example, at high altitudes, atmospheric pressures are lower than 1 Atm because there's less air over the area.

Question: are treaties the supreme law of the land
Passage: Supremacy Clause -- The Supremacy Clause of the United States Constitution (Article VI, Clause 2) establishes that the Constitution, federal laws made pursuant to it, and treaties made under its authority, constitute the supreme law of the land. It provides that state courts are bound by the supreme law; in case of conflict between federal and state law, the federal law must be applied. Even state constitutions are subordinate to federal law. In essence, it is a conflict-of-laws rule specifying that certain federal acts take priority over any state acts that conflict with federal law. In this respect, the Supremacy Clause follows the lead of Article XIII of the Articles of Confederation, which provided that ``Every State shall abide by the determination of the United States in Congress Assembled, on all questions which by this confederation are submitted to them.'' A constitutional provision announcing the supremacy of federal law, the Supremacy Clause assumes the underlying priority of federal authority, at least when that authority is expressed in the Constitution itself. No matter what the federal government or the states might wish to do, they have to stay within the boundaries of the Constitution. This makes the Supremacy Clause the cornerstone of the whole American political structure.
Explanation: The Supremaity Clause is the clause in our Constitution that says state laws must follow the laws set forth in and by our federal Constitution and Bill of Rights.  This is so because the Clause says that when there is conflict, state statutes must give way to the "supreme law" of our country. The "law" referred to in this Clause includes both the U.S. Constitution as well as federal statutes passed by Congress. State statutes that are in conflict must yield to these laws. For example, if a state passed a law that prohibited the use of alcohol, this law would be in direct conflict to a federal statute that made it legal for an adult to drink alcohol. Under theSupremecy Clause, such a prohibition would have no force or effect.

Question: is it possible to lose the ability to speak
Passage: Aphasia -- Aphasia is an inability to comprehend and formulate language because of damage to specific brain regions. This damage is typically caused by a cerebral vascular accident (stroke), or head trauma; however, these are not the only possible causes. To be diagnosed with aphasia, a person's speech or language must be significantly impaired in one (or several) of the four communication modalities following acquired brain injury or have significant decline over a short time period (progressive aphasia). The four communication modalities are auditory comprehension, verbal expression, reading and writing, and functional communication.
Explanation:
Aphasiaphasia is a form of speech impairment that can occur as a result of brain damage.  It is characterized by the inability of a patient to understand and/or formulate spoken language.  The four modalities of communication are: auditory comprehension, verbal expression (speaking), reading, writing. A patient with  aphasiaphasia will have speech that is significantly impaired in at least one of these four communication modalities.

  Based on the passage and the question, it is clear that a patient with aphasia will have speech that is significantly impaired  in at least one of the four communication modalities. 

The passage states that aphasic patients have impaired speech in at least one of the four communications modalities, namely: auditory  comprehension ,  verBAL expression (speaking) , reading  and writing. 

In this example, I would say that the patient has impaired verbal expression (spoken) because he has speech  that  is significantly  impeded in the  communication modality of verbal  expression. In other words, he has  speech that does not convey his intended meaning clearly. The patient is not able to express his thoughts clearly because his brain is damaged and does not function in a normal manner. His speech is impaired because it does  not convey the intended message clearly, which is to convey thoughts and ideas clearly and in proper sequence. Therefore, his speech  has impaired components that make it difficult to be understood by others. He has impairment in verbal communication because he is unable to communicate his ideas and thoughts in an effective manner, as required by his profession. Thus, in this case, aphasis is the result  of acquired brain injury, specifically a stroke. It is also important to note that this patient's language skills have not declined over time, so he does have some ability in auditory  comprehensal, but he would have this ability impaired as well. However, because this is his primary communication modality, this impairment is more significant. Because he also has impairments in reading  and writing as part of his communication impairment, they are considered secondary impairments. They are secondary because they do not significantly interfere with his ability to communicate effectively in his main communication mode. Finally, we can also consider his functional ability, or ability with which he communicates with others, to determine if he still has functional speech. Functional speech refers to the use of spoken and written language to carry on a conversation, even if the content of what is said is difficult for the person to hear or write. If a patient has functional speech, then he or she is able  to effectively communicate in all four modes of language, although the message may be difficult or complex for others to interpret. For example if a doctor were to ask a  patient with functional  speech to read a paragraph, that patient would be able  to read the paragraph and understand it, albeit with some difficulty. That patient could not write the text, however. So, while the functional aspect of this person’s speech would not be impaired, its effectiveness would. A patient who has aphatic speech will not have functional  language, only impaired  functional language

Question: is there such a thing as insulin resistance
Passage: Insulin resistance -- Insulin resistance (IR) is a pathological condition in which cells fail to respond normally to the hormone insulin. The body produces insulin when glucose starts to be released into the bloodstream from the digestion of carbohydrates (primarily) in the diet. Under normal conditions of insulin reactivity, this insulin response triggers glucose being taken into body cells, to be used for energy, and inhibits the body from using fat for energy, thereby causing the concentration of glucose in the blood to decrease as a result, staying within the normal range even when a large amount of carbohydrates is consumed. During insulin resistance, however, excess glucose is not sufficiently absorbed by cells even in the presence of insulin, thereby causing an increase in the level of blood sugar.
Explanation: Insulin is the key hormone that regulates the uptake of sugar (glucose) into cells. When the amount (level) of this hormone in blood is high, it can bind to its receptors on the surface of cells and trigger the internal machinery of the cells to absorb more sugar into those cells (uptake of excess sugar). When insulin is less reactive, cells are less able to take up sugar, which causes the sugar level in body to stay low. This is called insulin insensitivity.  When the insulin level is normal, body can effectively use sugar for fuel. However, when the intake of carbs is excessive, such as in a high-carbohydrate diet, insulin cannot effectively bind with its receptor on cells surface, causing cells become insulin-insensitive, leading to hyperinsulinemia. Hyperinsulinemic state can cause insulin resistant state. Insulinn resistance is one of causes of type 2 diabetes.

Question: is the 3 strikes law still in effect
Passage: Three-strikes law -- Twenty-eight states have some form of a ``three-strikes'' law. A person accused under such laws is referred to in a few states (notably Connecticut and Kansas) as a ``persistent offender'', while Missouri uses the unique term ``prior and persistent offender''. In most jurisdictions, only crimes at the felony level qualify as serious offenses; however, misdemeanor offenses can qualify for application of the three-strikes law in California, whose harsh application has been the subject of controversy.
Explanation:
The three strikes laws are still applicable in most states. Only crimes that are felonies in nature are considered serious, but some states allow misdemeanor convictions to be considered a strike. California is an example of this, as their three strike law was found to violate the constitution in 2009. 

California's three "striKES" law, passed in 1994, is one of several harsh sentencing laws that has come under fire from the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) and other groups. The law mandates life sentences for some third-time "violent" criminals, even if their crimes do not involve a firearm or a deadly weapon. Critics say the law is unconstitutional and is being used to send the wrong message to California's young people.


In 2009, a three judge panel of California’s Supreme Court ruled that the state’’ s three “striKEs” law violated the US Constitution’‘s ban on ex post facto laws.  The law mandated life imprisonment for certain repeat offenders, regardless of their actual culpability. In response to the ruling, California Attorney General Kamala Harris, who is a member of President Obama’'s cabinet, announced that she would not enforce the unconstitutional law and would seek to have it declared unconstitutional. However, in April 2011, she rescinded her decision and announced she was once again enforcing the “three strikes” laws, which she had previously said she wouldn’t do. She cited a need to protect public safety. Opponents of “Three Strikes” have called for its repeal, and in 2012, they succeeded in getting a ballot measure to repeal it on the California ballot. It was rejected by voters. 

 

Critics of "Three strikes" laws claim that they are unconstitutional because they violate ex-post facto clauses in the Constitution. These clauses prohibit the government from passing laws which retroactively increase punishment for past crimes. If a person has already been convicted of an offense, increasing the punishment to life in prison without the possibility of parole for a third offense is considered to increase the penalty for an existing offense and thus is found by the courts to constitute an ex ante increase in punishment.

 
  

However, some state laws do increase penalties for crimes committed before they were passed, yet these laws have been upheld by courts. For example, many states increase punishments for repeat drunk driving offenses, although such increases in penalties have long been part of state law for such offenses. This is because the increased penalties are for the third or subsequent offense of driving while intoxicated, not for any particular offense committed by a particular person. Thus, these increased punishmens do no increase a penalty retro-actively, since the penalties were already in place for prior offenses committed. "Strikes" statutes, however, increase only the sentence for third strike offenders. They do NOT increase any penalty that was in existence for second or first strike offenses that might be committed in future. Therefore, "three strike" penalties do constitute expost-facto increases, because prior to passage of these statutes the offender had no greater penalty than they already faced for their first or second offense. But these penalties DO NOT constitute a retroactive increase, so the ex posts facto clause does not apply.

Question: is it possible to win chess with only a king

Question: does passive transport go against the concentration gradient

However, in many cases (e.g. passive drug transport) the driving force of passive transport can not be simplified to the concentration gradient. Explanation: The passive diffusion of solute molecules is against concentration gradients because the solvation energy of a solvated molecule is proportional to its concentration and inversely proportional the molecular volume. Question: does a jury have to have 12 members
Passage: Jury -- The size of the jury is to provide a ``cross-section'' of the public. In Williams v. Florida, 399 U.S. 78 (1970), the Supreme Court of the United States ruled that a Florida state jury of six was sufficient, that ``the 12-man panel is not a necessary ingredient of ``trial by jury,'' and that respondent's refusal to impanel more than the six members provided for by Florida law ``did not violate petitioner's Sixth Amendment rights as applied to the States through the Fourteenth.'' In Ballew v. Georgia, 435 U.S. 223 (1978), the Supreme Court ruled that the number of jurors could not be reduced below six.
Explanation:
In Billew, a six-member jury was found to be sufficient. 

 

The Sixth amendment guarantees a defendant a "trial" by a panel of 12 jurors. The Supreme court has held that six is a sufficient number. 

Williams v Florida was a case where the state of Florida tried a man for a crime that required a minimum of 6 jurors to convict. However, they only had 6 available jurors, so they tried the man with 6. This man refused to accept the 6, and the court ruled he had been tried by 6 and was therefore guilty.

 

 

Balleww v Georgia was another case, where 6 was not sufficient for the defendant to get a trial. He was convicted by 5. When he appealed, he argued that 5 was insufficient, but the case was dismissed because the appellate court found that there was no case to appeal. 

 
These two cases together show that 6 is sufficient to guarantee a cross-sectional jury, however, it is insufficient if the State is unable to find 12 to try the individual. If the Sixth is going to mean anything, then the government must be able to follow it's rules. So, if a state is trying an individual, who has a right to a 6 member jury (the government), then they must follow the rules and find a way to make a 12 member panel. Otherwise, we have a situation where a person is denied their right because of a technicality. That is why the size must always be 6 members. There is no way around it. Question: is atmospheric pressure the same as air pressure

Pressure measures force per unit area, with SI units of Pascals (1 pascal = 1 newton per square metre, 1 N/m). On average, a column of air with a cross-sectional area of 1 square centimetre (cm), measured from mean (average) sea level to the top of Earth's atmosphere, has a mass of about 1.03 kilogram and exerts a force or ``weight'' of about 10.1 newtons or 2.37 lb, resulting in a pressure at sea level of about 10.1 N/cm or 101 kN/m (101 kilopascals, kPa). A column of air with a cross-sectional area of 1 in (6.45 cm) would have a mass of about 6.65 kg and a weight of about 65.4 N or 14.7 lb, resulting in a pressure of 10.1 N/cm or 14.7 lb/in.
Explanation: At sea-level, atmospheric (also called hydrostatical) pressure equals the force exerted by over-lying air divided by its cross sectional area. This is because at that point, all the air is above you, and the mass/weight of the overhanging air equals its density times its height. So, if you double the height of a 1 cm2 cross section of overhang air, its pressure will be half.

Question: can a federal law override a state law
Passage: Supremacy Clause -- The Supremacy Clause of the United States Constitution (Article VI, Clause 2) establishes that the Constitution, federal laws made pursuant to it, and treaties made under its authority, constitute the supreme law of the land. It provides that state courts are bound by the supreme law; in case of conflict between federal and state law, the federal law must be applied. Even state constitutions are subordinate to federal law. In essence, it is a conflict-of-laws rule specifying that certain federal acts take priority over any state acts that conflict with federal law. In this respect, the Supremacy Clause follows the lead of Article XIII of the Articles of Confederation, which provided that ``Every State shall abide by the determination of the United States in Congress Assembled, on all questions which by this confederation are submitted to them.'' A constitutional provision announcing the supremacy of federal law, the Supremacy Clause assumes the underlying priority of federal authority, at least when that authority is expressed in the Constitution itself. This makes the Supremacy Clause the cornerstone of the whole American political structure.
Explanation:
The Supremaity Clause is the foundational rule of American law that establishes the priority and supremacy (over any conflicting state or federal legislation) of laws expressed or implied in or derived from the US Constitution over state laws that are inconsistent with such laws. The clause provides a "conflict- of- laws rule" specifying the order in which federal statutes and regulations are to be given effect. 

 
In essence the clause establishes a system of dual sovereignty, in that both the state governments and the Federal government have supremacy over the laws of each other.  The clause is found in Article VI of our Constitution and provides:

"This Constitution... shall be the Supreme Law of The Land; and THE JUDGES IN EVERY STATE SHALL BE bound thereby, ANY THING IN THE CONSTITUTION TO THE CONTRARY notwithstanding."

          A DNA molecule is comprised primarily of deoxynucleotides, a ribose sugar, two phosphate groups, one hydrogen and one oxygen. Each de oxynucleotide is linked to four de oxyribonuclotides through phosphodiester bonds, forming a chain of nucleotides. Nucleotides are joined together in a specific order, with the first four nucleotides being guanosine triphosphates (GTP), adenylyl tri phosphates(ATP), uridine triphos phates (UTP) and guanylylimidodiphosphate (GDP). The order of these nucleotides is important, as it is used in DNA replication and is essential for protein translation. There are three main types of nucleic acids: DNA (deoxy-ribo nucleic acid), RNA (ribono nucleic acid) and PNA (peptide nucleic acide). DNA can form double stranded helical structures, called DNA double helix, where the two strands are held together by hydrogen bonds. RNA can also form a double-stranded structure, known as an RNA double strand, in which the ribo-nucleotides form hydrogen-bonded helices. P NA, on the other hand, is single stranded and can bind to complementary sequences on DNA or RNA. Proteins are made up of one or more polypeptide chains, each made from a sequence of amino acids. Amino acids are typically composed  of a carboxyl group, an amino group and  a side chain. Some amino groups can have substitutions, for example glycine can be substituted by alanine or serine or threonine can replace valine or isoleucine in proteins . Other amino acid substitutions can lead to changes in their physical properties, including amphiphilicity, hydrophobicity and hydrophilcity. Hydrophobic amino acids are typically found in regions of protein that interact with other molecules, like binding sites. 
          
       A membrane separates the inside of living thing from the outside. Membranes are primarily made up of phospholipid molecules. Phospholipids consist of two fatty acid chains and two phosphoric acid groups. Fatty acids consist mainly of carbon atoms with various numbers of carbons and heteroatoms such oxygen or nitrogen. Heteroatom is any element other than carbon and hydrogen. Lipids are amphiphilic, meaning they have both hydrophilic and hydrophobic groups on their surface. Their properties are dependent on the number and type of heteratoms. Cholesterol is an example of lipid that has a hydrophobic group on its  surface. Bilayer structure is where two lipid layers are present, separated by a small amount of water. One of its main functions is to act as a barrier to protect the contents of that membrane from outside environment. Another function of sphinge- myelin is its role as energy source. Energy is released when sphingingomyeline is broken down to produce adenosine diphosphates and choline.
